Substituting $n_{e}(t)=a \tanh b t$ in (A1.2) and separating it in the independent functions (hyperbolic, or 1 and $\left.e^{x}\right)$, one gets

$$
a=\sqrt{\frac{Z_{e x t}}{r}}
\tag{A1.4}
$$
$$
b=\sqrt{r Z_{e x t}}
\tag{A1.5}
$$

According to equation (A1.4) the number density of electronsat steady-state is expressed in terms of the external ionizer activity as

$$
n_{e 1}=\sqrt{\frac{Z_{e x t 1}}{r}}
\tag{A2.1}
$$
$$
n_{e 2}=\sqrt{\frac{Z_{e x t 2}}{r}}
\tag{A2.2}
$$
$$
n_{e}=\sqrt{\frac{Z_{e x t 1}+Z_{e x t 2}}{r}}
\tag{A2.3}
$$

Thus,the following analogue of the Pythagorean theorem is obtained as

$$
n_{e}=\sqrt{n_{e 1}^{2}+n_{e 2}^{2}}=20.0 \cdot 10^{10} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}
\tag{A2.4}
$$

In the steady state, the balance equations of electrons and ions in the tube volume take the form

$$
Z_{\text {ext }} S L=r n_{e} n_{i} S L+\frac{I_{e}}{e}
\tag{A3.1}
$$
$$
Z_{\text {ext }} S L=r n_{e} n_{i} S L+\frac{I_{i}}{e}
\tag{A3.2}
$$

It follows from equations (A3.1) and (A3.2) that the ion and electron currents are equal, i.e.

$$
I_{e}=I_{i}
\tag{A3.3}
$$

At the same time the total current in each tube section is the sum of the electron and ion currents

$$
I=I_{e}+I_{i}
\tag{A3.4}
$$

By definition ofthe current density the following relations hold

$$
I_{e}=\frac{I}{2}=e n_{e} v S=e \beta n_{e} E S
\tag{A3.5}
$$
$$
I_{i}=\frac{I}{2}=e n_{i} v S=e \beta n_{i} E S
\tag{A3.6}
$$

Substituting (A3.5) and (A3.6) into (A3.1) and (A3.2), the following quadratic equation for the current is derived

$$
Z_{e x t} S L=r S L\left(\frac{I}{2 e \beta E S}\right)^{2}+\frac{I}{2 e}
\tag{A3.7}
$$

The electric field strength in the gas is equal to

$$
E=\frac{U}{L}
\tag{A3.8}
$$

and solution to the quadratic equation (A3.7) takes the form

$$
I=\frac{e \beta^{2} U^{2} S}{r L^{3}}\left(-1 \pm \sqrt{1+\frac{4 r Z_{e x t} L^{4}}{\beta^{2} U^{2}}}\right)
\tag{A3.9}
$$



It is obvious that only positive root does make sense, i.e.

$$
I=\frac{e \beta^{2} U^{2} S}{r L^{3}}\left(\sqrt{1+\frac{4 r Z_{e x t} L^{4}}{\beta^{2} U^{2}}}-1\right)
\tag{A3.10}
$$

At low voltages (A3.10) simplifies and gives the following expression

$$
I=2 U e \beta \sqrt{\frac{Z_{e x t}}{r}} \frac{S}{L}
\tag{A4.1}
$$

which is actually the Ohm law.

Using the well-known relation

$$
R=\frac{U}{I}
\tag{A4.2}
$$

together with

$$
R=\rho \frac{L}{S}
\tag{A4.3}
$$

one gets

$$
\rho=\frac{1}{2 e \beta} \sqrt{\frac{r}{Z_{e x t}}}
\tag{A4.4}
$$

