Apply Newton's law to mass $M_{1}$ :

$$
M_{1} \frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} \vec{r}_{1}}{\mathrm{~d} t^{2}}=G \frac{M_{1} M_{2}}{\left|\vec{r}_{2}-\vec{r}_{1}\right|^{2}} \frac{\vec{r}_{2}-\vec{r}_{1}}{\left|\vec{r}_{2}-\overrightarrow{r_{1}}\right|}
\tag{1}
$$

Use, from eq. (1) of the question sheet

$$
\vec{r}_{2}=-\frac{M_{1}}{M_{2}} \vec{r}_{1}
\tag{2}
$$

in eq. (1) above, to obtain

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} \vec{r}_{1}}{\mathrm{~d} t^{2}}=-\frac{G M_{2}^{3}}{\left(M_{1}+M_{2}\right)^{2} r_{1}^{2}} \frac{\vec{r}_{1}}{r_{1}} .
\tag{3}
$$

The total energy of the system is the sum of the two kinetic energies plus the gravitational potential energy. For circular motions, the linear velocity of each of the masses reads

$$
\left|\vec{v}_{1}\right|=r_{1} \Omega, \quad\left|\vec{v}_{2}\right|=r_{2} \Omega
\tag{4}
$$

Thus, the total energy is

$$
E=\frac{1}{2}\left(M_{1} r_{1}^{2}+M_{2} r_{2}^{2}\right) \Omega^{2}-\frac{G M_{1} M_{2}}{L}
\tag{5}
$$

Now,

$$
\left(M_{1} r_{1}-M_{2} r_{2}\right)^{2}=0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad M_{1} r_{1}^{2}+M_{2} r_{2}^{2}=\mu L^{2}
\tag{6}
$$

Thus,

$$
E=\frac{1}{2} \mu L^{2} \Omega^{2}-G \frac{M \mu}{L} .
\tag{7}
$$

Energy (3) of the question sheet can be interpreted as describing a system of a mass $\mu$ in a circular orbit with angular velocity $\Omega$, radius $L$, around a mass $M$ (at rest). Equating the gravitational acceleration to the centripetal acceleration:

$$
G \frac{M}{L^{2}}=\Omega^{2} L
\tag{8}
$$

This is indeed Kepler's third law (for circular orbits). Then, from 7,

$$
E=-\frac{1}{2} G \frac{M \mu}{L}
\tag{9}
$$

